#: ../../SO1.md:561
msgid "Step 2:  Select a productivity index"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:563
msgid "The NDVI is recommended as the default index for countries to use in the absence of evidence to indicate that an alternative index is better suited to their landscape. Although NDVI is the most widely used and well-known vegetation index, its main limitations are that it can be sensitive to variations in soil background conditions and that it tends to saturate at high vegetation cover and biomass levels. This can reduce the accuracy of NPP, biomass and green cover models in tropical rainforest or arid regions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:565
msgid "Other indices, such as the EVI, may also be suitable. Although some of these indices may perform better than NDVI under some specific vegetation conditions, they may require additional adjustment when applied to vast areas and different land cover types. Consequently, despite its limitations, NDVI is currently considered the universal option for regional- and national-level land productivity calculation, considering that extensive research has demonstrated the strong relationship between NDVI and primary productivity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:567
msgid "Step 3: Estimate annual productivity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:569
msgid "The estimation of annual productivity should take into consideration that, due to the natural cycles of growth and senescence of vegetation, NPP is best represented by a time series of observations captured during the full growing season. Therefore, for each pixel location, the annual productivity will be the integral of values from the start to the end of the growing season of the selected productivity index. Areas with increasing NPP should be interpreted as improving, unless assessed otherwise at country level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:571
msgid "Further indications on options to estimate the start and length of the growing season are given in section 4.2.4.1 of the [Good Practice Guidance for SDG Indicator 15.3.1](https://www.unccd.int/publications/good-practice-guidance-sdg-indicator-1531-proportion-land-degraded-over-total-land)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:573
msgid "Step 4: Calculate land productivity metrics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:575
msgid "Estimating changes in productivity over time is based on the multi-temporal analysis of the annual productivity using three metrics:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:577
msgid "**Trend**: measures the trajectory of change in annual productivity over the long term per pixel;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:579
msgid "**State**: compares the current to historical annual productivity per pixel;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:581
msgid "**Performance**: indicates the level of local annual productivity over an area compared with other areas with a similar land productivity potential."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:583
msgid "The changes observed in each of the three metrics are combined to determine persistent land productivity trajectories represented in five classes comparable with the default dataset provided by JRC (see table 13 below). They are also used to determine whether a pixel is degraded or not degraded in the baseline period and whether a pixel is degrading, improving or stable in the reporting period (see Step 5)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:585
msgid "Productivity Trend"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:587
msgid "To calculate the productivity Trend, Parties should determine the trajectory of change in productivity over a 16-year time interval on a pixel level. The Trend metric is calculated over an interval of 16 years for both the baseline (2000–2015) and the reporting period (i.e. a 16-year period ending in the last year of data being reported (i.e. 2004–2019)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:589
msgid "The Trend metric is calculated by fitting a linear regression model to the time series and determining the significance of the trend slope by calculating its z-score. Positive z-scores indicate a trend of increasing productivity, while negative scores indicate decreasing productivity. Z-scores reflect the magnitude of the slope, with scores of higher magnitude indicating greater strength of the ongoing process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:591
msgid "Box 1. What is a z-score"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:596
msgid "A z-score measures how many standard deviations above or below the mean a data point is. The formula for calculating a z-score is reported below, where ‘z’ is the z-score:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:599
msgid "$z = \\frac{data\\ point – mean}{standard\\ deviation}$"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:602
msgid "&nbsp;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:604
msgid "Important facts about z-scores:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:605
msgid "A positive z-score indicates that the data point is above average."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:606
msgid "A negative z-score indicates that the data point is below average."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:607
msgid "A z-score close to 0 indicates that the data point is close to average."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:608
msgid "A data point can be considered unusual if its z-score is above or below 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:611
msgid "As recommended in the [Good Practice Guidance for SDG Indicator 15.3.1](https://www.unccd.int/publications/good-practice-guidance-sdg-indicator-1531-proportion-land-degraded-over-total-land), z-score intervals may be set as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:613
msgid "z-score < –1.96 = degrading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:614
msgid "z-score < –1.28 AND ≥ –1.96 = potentially degrading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:615
#: ../../SO1.md:653
msgid "z-score ≥ –1.28 AND ≤ 1.28 = no significant change"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:616
#: ../../SO1.md:654
msgid "z-score > 1.28 AND ≤ 1.96 = potentially improving"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:617
#: ../../SO1.md:655
msgid "z-score > 1.96 = improving"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:619
msgid "However, for the purposes of UNCCD reporting, the five classes above are simplified into the following three classes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:621
#: ../../SO1.md:659
msgid "z-score < –1.28 = degrading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:622
#: ../../SO1.md:660
msgid "z-score ≥ -1.28 AND ≤ 1.28"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:623
#: ../../SO1.md:661
msgid "z-score > 1.28 = improving"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:625
msgid "The pixels with the lowest negative z-score level (< –1.28) are considered degraded and other areas are considered not degraded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:627
msgid "Productivity State"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:629
msgid "Productivity State is determined by comparing the mean annual NPP of the three most recent years to the distribution of annual NPP values observed in the preceding 13 years. More specifically, this entails comparing values for the years 2013–2015 with the years 2000–2012 for the baseline, and the 3 most recent years with the preceding 13 years for the reporting period."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:631
msgid "Parties should make the following calculations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:637
msgid "Baseline"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:638
msgid "Reporting period"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:639
msgid "A = Mean annual NPP 2013–2015"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:640
msgid "A = Mean annual NPP of the 3 most recent years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:641
msgid "B = Mean annual NPP 2000–2012"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:642
msgid "B = Mean annual NPP of the 13 preceding years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:643
msgid "C = Standard deviation 2000–2012"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:644
msgid "C = Standard deviation of the 13 preceding years"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:645
#: ../../SO1.md:646
msgid "z-score = (A – B) / C"
