#: ../../SO1.md:649
msgid "Class definitions for the Z scores are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:651
msgid "z-score < –1.96 = degraded"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:652
msgid "z-score < –1.28 AND ≥ –1.96 = at risk of degrading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:657
msgid "Similar to the productivity Trend, the above-mentioned five classes are reduced to three when reporting data to UNCCD:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:663
msgid "For the purposes of calculating the land productivity sub-indicator, UNCCD recommends considering only the area of the lowest negative z-score level (< –1.96) as degraded. Areas in other z-score classes should be considered as not degraded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:665
msgid "Productivity Performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:667
msgid "In contrast to Trend and State, which are temporal metrics, productivity Performance is a spatial metric involving benchmarking the level of local plant productivity relative to other land units (i.e. other pixels) within the same Land Cover/Ecosystem Functional Unit (LCEU)[^2]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:671
msgid "Productivity Performance is calculated by comparing the mean annual productivity value per pixel with the maximum productivity index value observed within the same LCEU for a given assessment period. Pixels are considered degraded when their productivity potential is less than a half of the maximum value observed in a given LCEU. The maximum value is in turn defined as the 90th percentile of pixel values in the LCEU (NPP{sub}`max`)[^3]. Therefore, productivity Performance values close to 1 represent pixels in which productivity is close to the highest level for that land unit in that period."
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:675
msgid "The resulting dataset would then include only two classes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:677
msgid "z-score < 0.5 NPP{sub}`max` = degrading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:678
msgid "z-score ≥ 0.5 NPP{sub}`max` = improving"
msgstr ""

#: ../../SO1.md:680
msgid "The productivity Performance in the reporting periods should be calculated from the mean of the annual productivity assessments over the years between the previous (or baseline) assessment up to the current year."
msgstr ""

